pan><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">is an international, non-g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">overnmental, non-political, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">non-profit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> organization founded in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">1996 in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> Holon, Israel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">at the Wolfson Medical </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Centre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">WMC) with the mission of improving the quality of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">paediatric</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> cardiac care for children from low to lower-middle income countries suffering from rheumatic and congenital heart disease and creating </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">centres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> of com</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">petence in these countries. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">SACH is fully dedicated to the idea that every child deserves the best medical treatment available, regardless of the child's nationality, religion, race, gender or financial situation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Due to the fact that over 50% of the child</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">ren, who receive cardiac care from SACH, reside in the West Bank and Gaza, it is of significance for SACH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> to respond to this inquiry.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">INTRODUCTION</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> AND BACKGROUND</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.73pt; padding-left:4.27pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Save a Child's Heart (SACH) is an Israeli based international humanitarian nongovernmental org</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">anization providing life-saving heart surgery and follow-up care for children from the West Bank, Gaza and many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">low to lower-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">middle income</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> countries within Africa, Asia and other parts of the Middle East.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> SACH strives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> to improve the quality of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">paediatric</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">ardiac care for children from around the world </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">suffering from rheumatic and congenital heart disease</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">The organization</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">al efforts provide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> holistic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> cardiac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> care </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">encompass</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> evaluation,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> diagnoses, treatment and follow-up of each patient </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">while simultaneously creating </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">centres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> of medical competence in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">low to lower-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">middle income countries that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">enabl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> local physicians to treat </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">patients within </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">own </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.73pt; padding-left:4.27pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">SACH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">, with Special Consultative Status under the UN’s Economic and Social Cou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">ncil (ECOSOC),</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> is a hospital-based project offering all of its varied services in cooperation with the Wolfson Medical </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Centre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> (WMC) in Holon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">, Israel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">.  Since its inception in 1996, the organization has operated on over 3,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">00 children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">from 48</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> different coun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">tries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> suffering from heart disease</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> with Palestinian children representing over 1,600 of these operations.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.73pt; padding-left:4.27pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">SACH’s mission is accomplished by: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Bringing children in need of heart surgery, to Israel, whose countries have a lack of knowledge and necessary in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">frastructure to provide </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">lifesaving</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> cardiac care </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">SACH has treated over 3,300 children suffering from congenital and rheumatic heart disease aging from infancy to 18 years of age who reside in 48 countries where adequate medical care is unavailable. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Givin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">g in-depth postgraduate training to medical personnel from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">low to lower-middle income</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> countries at the WMC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> –</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> SACH has trained </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">over</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">90</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> physicians and nurses from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">partnering </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">countries at the WMC, an affiliate of the Sackler School of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Medicine at Tel Aviv </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">University</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">. The training</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">recognized</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> by the MASHAV department at the Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs as conforming </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> aims for teaching self-help.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.29pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Travelling to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">low or lower-middle income countries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">in order to evaluate pre- and post-operati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">ve patients, together with local personnel in joint cardiology clinics, operate on patients together with local physicians and offer onsite training in various fields of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">paediatric</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> cardiac care</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">. SACH has evaluated more than 8,000 children in different loca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">tions both in Israel and abroad. SACH has also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> completed 16 teaching missions overseas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">, performing more than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">200</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> life-saving surgeries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">alongside local personnel.</span></li></ul><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.73pt; padding-left:4.27pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">SACH gives credence to the idea that every child deserves the best medical treatment available, regardless of the child's nationality, religion, race, gender or financial status. While around 44% of SACH’s patients come from countries outside of the Middle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> East, the other 56% comprise mainly Palestinians from the West Bank and Gaza as well as a minority of Iraqis, Jordanians and most recently Syrians due to the ensuing civil war. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Cooperative efforts, related to cardiac care for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">children, have existed for ov</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">er 15 years </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">between SACH medical staff in Israel and Palestinian cardiologists in the West Bank and Gaza. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.73pt; padding-left:4.27pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">In order to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> development of the Palestinian Authority’s healthcare system in the West Bank, SACH </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">established</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> a medical initiative bringi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">ng together Palestinian and Israeli medical personnel while simultaneously </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">maintaining</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">holistic cardiac care </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">provided </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">to Palestinian children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> since SACH’s inception</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">initiative</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> involved building </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">bridges of peace</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> between the two </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">societies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> under the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Heart of the Matter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> Program</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.73pt; padding-left:4.27pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">The formal establishment of this program also helped institute the relationship between SACH and the Palestinian Ministry of Health (PMOH) with the signing of a Memorandum of Understanding on February 13, 2012.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">The MOU provide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">s formalization of the cooperation between SACH and the PMOH, co-sponsorship of PMOH in the treatment of Palestinian children and approval of the training program by the PMOH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">, therefore ensuring the creation of a National </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Centre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> of Cardiac Excellence based</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> in Ramallah.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.73pt; padding-left:4.27pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Relevant Facts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> to consider</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.64pt; padding-left:7.56pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">To date 1,877 children from the Palestinian Authority, Iraq, Jordan, Morocco and most recently Syria have re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">ceived life-saving cardiac care. The majority receiving care are Palestinian with a representation of over </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">1,600 children.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.64pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Over </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">6,000 P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">alestinian children have been examined at SACH’s weekly free cardiology clinic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> at the WMC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.64pt; padding-left:7.56pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Twenty-one Palestinian physicians and three Palestinian nurses have participated in SACH Outreach Training programs.</span></li></ul><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.73pt; padding-left:4.27pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">The Heart of the Matter Program maintains two intrinsic aspects to its design; it preserves collaborative efforts between Palestinian and Israeli medical staff through the provision of cardiac care to Palestinian children and provides an outreach training </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">program </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">for up to five years</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> for physicians and nurses from the Palestinian Authority. The capacity building efforts of the program include</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Palestinian doctors and nurses working alongside Israeli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> medical </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">personnel to treat Palestinian children coming to t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">he WMC for cardiac care and being significantly involved with medical assessments at the weekly Palestinian cardiology clinic. The end result of these capacity building efforts includes the creation of a National </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Centre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> of Cardiac Excellence based in Ramal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">lah</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> and the purchase of much needed medical equipment for the WMC and PMOH.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.73pt; padding-left:4.27pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Consequently, the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">programs’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">capacity building </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">efforts not only impact the direct beneficiaries (children receiving cardiac care and Palestinian and Israeli medical personnel involv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">ed in the program) but also larger </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">groups</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">such as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> the 200 Palestinian and Israeli medical personnel cooperatively working to help these children, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">dozens of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> government and organizational officials involved with the PMOH and SACH, the 4,000 Israeli and Pales</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">tinian family members of patients intermingling at the WMC and the subsequent 20,000 extended family members interacting with these beneficiaries.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">The program</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> currently receives support from diverse international and local government entities such as the E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">U Partnership for Peace, USAID, Israel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> Ministry for Regional Cooperation and Palest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">inian Ministry of Health. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Furthermore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">SACH UK</span><span style="font-fam